WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:28.879
Cool. Thank you, Winston. And, yeah. Thanks, everyone, for being here. I'm excited to show

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:36.240
you another project that Joe and I have been working on this year, Shinymeta. And I want

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:45.080
to start off sort of by first sharing that it's pretty crazy for me to be up here doing

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:51.000
this talk and standing in front of you as a RStudio software engineer, because it seems

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:59.720
like not that long ago, I was a grad student struggling with learning R and really, you

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:04.400
know, not having a ton of fun with it and certainly didn't expect to become a software

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:12.680
engineer at any point within the next, say, ten years. And in my second year of grad school,

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:18.839
I discovered like ggplot2 and things that became the Tidyverse. And right around that

00:01:18.839 --> 00:01:25.599
same time, you know, I was becoming more productive with my R programming. And I then

00:01:25.599 --> 00:01:30.919
discovered this thing called Shiny, and it just kind of blew me away, like how magical

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:39.440
it was to, like, take my analysis and, with very minimal changes, turn it into an interactive

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:45.919
web app. So that was really the point where I sort of became sort of, like, really into

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:51.320
R and really into programming. And I was just sort of blown away at how I could enable

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:57.959
others to sort of tease apart the data that I was working with and also found it really

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:06.279
useful for teaching when I was a grad student as well. So this interactive power that Shiny

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:11.300
brings to the table is really, really great. But we should acknowledge that whenever we

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:19.220
make the decision to use an interactive tool for our work as data scientists, as statisticians,

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:24.059
that decision to use an interactive tool over reproducible code is going to come at the

00:02:24.059 --> 00:02:31.300
cost of reproducibility. So if we focus in on Shiny, really the core problem here is

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:38.339
that in order to do its thing, Shiny sort of depends on the user events to sort of drive

00:02:38.339 --> 00:02:44.979
the application logic. And this Shiny runtime execution that sort of determines, like, what

00:02:44.979 --> 00:02:52.240
R code to execute in response to, you know, what user events. And at least for a number

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:59.820
of years, we've been able to mostly work around this problem in focus of user events through

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:05.660
Shiny bookmarking. So this at least allows us to save the state of the application at

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:12.940
any point in time and in theory be able to come back to the state of the application

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:18.940
sort of assuming that, you know, the app is there available and allowing us to sort of

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:25.539
restore the state of the application. But especially if we're not, like, if we don't

00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:31.339
have control over the application, if somebody else is hosting that for us, our bookmarking

00:03:31.339 --> 00:03:36.100
URL that we go to to go back to the state of our application, if that app is no longer

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:43.300
available, we're kind of out of luck. So in that sense, we still lack some sense of permanence

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:50.820
that we get from reproducible R code. And even if the app is working and we can sort

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:55.460
of replicate the user events and get back to the state of the application, we still

00:03:55.460 --> 00:04:01.059
sort of lack some sense of transparency in the sense that those outputs are still locked

00:04:01.059 --> 00:04:08.139
behind a graphical user interface. And if, even if I could get at the source code behind

00:04:08.139 --> 00:04:14.539
the application, sort of the core R domain logic that I might be interested in verifying

00:04:14.539 --> 00:04:22.019
is correct, that's still sort of intertwined with Shiny's runtime engine and it's sort

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:29.820
of hard to know exactly, like, what R code is being executed at any point in time. So

00:04:29.820 --> 00:04:35.540
the goal here is we sort of want to enable you to eliminate that Shiny runtime dependency

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:43.660
in some sense, where we want to enable you to write Shiny apps that can generate R code

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:49.820
to essentially mimic the code that it's executing so that you can run that code without Shiny

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:57.660
and without having to, like, duplicate that logic yourself in multiple places.

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:04.059
So the project that we're working on to help you enable this feature is the Shiny

00:05:04.059 --> 00:05:10.619
meta R package. And this provides tools for you as the Shiny app developer to capture

00:05:10.619 --> 00:05:18.140
the core essential domain logic that is powering your application and exposing it as code to

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:23.420
users that they can run outside of the Shiny app.

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:27.899
So to demonstrate how Shiny meta works, we're going to work through this real basic Shiny

00:05:27.899 --> 00:05:34.540
app example. It just has a text input box where I can type in a R package name. And

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:39.540
as I type in different packages, I can get a new time series of the number of downloads

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:45.179
for the past year for that given R package.

00:05:45.179 --> 00:05:53.220
So the goal is to modify this Shiny application and add an ability for this code to update

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:58.660
every time I enter a new package and give me reproducible R code back that I can copy

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:10.100
and paste into a new fresh R session and essentially mimic the execution of this Shiny application.

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:17.820
So here is the entire implementation of that basic Shiny app. As with any Shiny app, there's

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:23.700
two main components. The UI object at the top is for the user interface. It just has

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:29.500
the text input for where I put the package name. And then the plot output sort of container

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:32.779
for the time series plot.

00:06:32.779 --> 00:06:37.100
And then the server logic below that is going to determine how to take that input from the

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:44.779
text input box and create the ggplot time series for the plot output.

00:06:44.779 --> 00:06:50.140
So we're going to zoom in on the server functionality. And the first step with adding Shiny meta

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:56.779
integration is determine where in the logic of my Shiny app is the core domain logic that

00:06:56.779 --> 00:06:58.459
I want to provide to my user.

00:06:58.459 --> 00:07:02.899
And we're going to walk through these three different steps here. So let's focus in on

00:07:02.899 --> 00:07:11.100
step one. This downloads reactive. Essentially, it's taking the current value of this text

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:16.380
input, and it's referencing that as input dollar package, feeding that into this CRAN

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:22.140
downloads function to give me the previous, like the downloads for the last year for this

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:24.420
package.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:29.220
And then in the downloads rolling reactive, we take the return value of the downloads

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:37.299
reactive. And if it's a sensible value, we will use dplyr and this zoo package to compute

00:07:37.299 --> 00:07:45.260
a weekly rolling average, mainly just for visualization purposes.

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:51.059
And notice that I haven't highlighted this particular part of the reactive expression.

00:07:51.059 --> 00:07:57.940
This part is mainly just here to improve the interactive experience of the Shiny app and

00:07:57.940 --> 00:08:05.739
doesn't really have any sort of, you know, domain context in terms of actually producing

00:08:05.739 --> 00:08:12.619
the plot output. This is assuming we have a valid R package name is not really necessary

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:16.339
to be here.

00:08:16.339 --> 00:08:21.220
So we'll talk a little bit about that in the next step. But in the last step here, we'll

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:29.100
just take the return value of the downloads rolling and feed that into ggplot.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:33.219
So domain logic here identified in blue.

00:08:33.219 --> 00:08:41.659
Then the next step is to use Shiny meta's meta reactive building blocks and capture

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:47.260
that domain logic that we've highlighted in blue. And those Shiny meta reactive building

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:51.659
blocks are highlighted in pink.

00:08:51.659 --> 00:08:58.619
So the downloads reactive has just changed from reactive to meta reactive. So meta reactive

00:08:58.619 --> 00:09:04.580
will assume that the entire expression is domain logic that you want to export to the

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:06.820
user.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:12.580
But in this case of the downloads rolling, where we have just part of the reactive expression

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:19.580
that we want to capture as domain logic, we use meta reactive 2 instead, and then we can

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:25.820
just target a particular part of that reactive expression with this meta expert function

00:09:25.979 --> 00:09:32.099
and just tag that as the domain logic that we want to export.

00:09:32.099 --> 00:09:35.900
And then finally, for rendering functions, since these are a little bit different in

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:42.539
the sense that anybody can implement their own rendering function, we meta renders kind

00:09:42.539 --> 00:09:47.380
of like a decorator function where it takes the rendering function as the first argument.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:49.859
Here it's rendered plot.

00:09:49.859 --> 00:09:53.619
And then the second argument is the reactive expression.

00:09:53.619 --> 00:10:01.380
Right. So now we've in some sense captured the domain logic with these meta reactive

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:06.859
equivalents to Shiny reactive building blocks.

00:10:06.859 --> 00:10:15.299
And the next part is to, within sort of the domain logic, identify any reactive reads.

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:22.539
So at the very top here, I'm reading the current value of the text input.

00:10:22.539 --> 00:10:29.580
And then down below, I'm reading the return value of the downloads reactive expression

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:37.539
and reading the return value of the downloads rolling reactive.

00:10:37.539 --> 00:10:42.659
So this part is probably going to be the hardest part to see, but once we've identified the

00:10:42.659 --> 00:10:50.979
reactive reads in blue, then we're going to mark those reactive reads with a dot operator.

00:10:50.979 --> 00:10:57.520
And this is going to essentially provide a signal to the Shiny meta code generation mode

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:04.380
and let it know that when we go to generate code from these reactive components, I want

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:09.900
to essentially let Shiny meta know that these should be replaced with either a static value

00:11:10.059 --> 00:11:18.539
that it represents or a variable name that will represent the value that it really represents.

00:11:18.539 --> 00:11:23.380
So we'll see that in a second.

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:29.179
I also want to point out that this dot dot operator, you can think of it in some sense

00:11:29.179 --> 00:11:35.580
as the, like the bang bang from Rlang, in the sense that you can use it like a unquoting

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:43.619
operator where if you wrap any sort of R code that's not reactive, it will just evaluate

00:11:43.619 --> 00:11:47.099
that code instead of returning the expression.

00:11:47.099 --> 00:11:56.859
So we'll see how this can be used to essentially like hard code a dynamic value.

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:04.820
And then really the last step to actually generating the code to mimic the code that

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:09.940
the Shiny app is actually executing when it goes to like fill in the outputs of the

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:13.979
Shiny app is to use this expand chain function.

00:12:13.979 --> 00:12:18.739
And here I'm just providing it the plot outputs object.

00:12:18.739 --> 00:12:24.299
But if you had multiple objects, you could provide multiple outputs to this function.

00:12:24.299 --> 00:12:28.820
And not only will it return the domain logic in a way that can run outside of the Shiny

00:12:28.859 --> 00:12:38.859
app, but it will also figure out sort of the minimal amount of code necessary to do so.

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:44.700
So when we actually call expand chain, it will return all of the logic that we've captured

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:48.299
with the metareactive building blocks.

00:12:48.299 --> 00:12:52.780
And before returning, it's going to walk through this code and it's going to look for these

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.380
dot dot operators.

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:59.140
And it's going to find this first dot dot operator and it's going to kind of recognize

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:02.500
that it's a marked input value.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:08.940
And in this case, since this is just, well, what it will do is return it with the current

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:16.059
value that's in the text input box when we go and actually call this expand chain function.

00:13:16.059 --> 00:13:18.979
All right.

00:13:18.979 --> 00:13:23.020
And then this part, there's nothing really special in a reactive sense about this R code

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:26.340
inside this dot dot operator.

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:32.260
But I'm essentially just putting the date as it stands today, the day that I'm generating

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:35.739
this code in a human readable format.

00:13:35.739 --> 00:13:42.059
So this dot dot operator can in some sense be used to not only like hard code a dynamic

00:13:42.059 --> 00:13:48.700
value, but also if you kind of master metaprogramming in some sense, if you're familiar with bang

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:54.299
bang from Rlang, you can use it in ways to make your code that you're generating a little

00:13:54.299 --> 00:13:56.260
more human readable.

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:59.359
All right.

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:03.179
So now it's going to go to the next dot dot operator and it's going to recognize, oh,

00:14:03.179 --> 00:14:05.419
this downloads reactive read.

00:14:05.419 --> 00:14:12.739
This actually represents a value that now actually exists in this code that I'm generating.

00:14:12.739 --> 00:14:16.659
Because it's going to recognize that, you know, the downloads reactive that we now have

00:14:16.659 --> 00:14:21.659
static code for, this is a variable that now exists.

00:14:21.659 --> 00:14:30.299
So I can just simply replace this reactive read with the variable name.

00:14:30.299 --> 00:14:33.460
And then it will do the same thing for the downloads rolling.

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:39.739
Now that we're essentially creating a new variable, downloads rolling, I can reuse that

00:14:39.739 --> 00:14:43.979
in the ggplot visualization call.

00:14:43.979 --> 00:14:46.900
All right.

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:53.940
So for most serious applications, your reactive code is going to rely on some setup code,

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:59.780
sort of like some subset maybe of the setup code that, you know, you have above your launching

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:04.700
of the Shiny app to do things like loading libraries and reading in data, these sort

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:06.380
of things.

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:12.219
And at least one way that you can approach this today is you can quote that subset of

00:15:12.219 --> 00:15:18.580
code and provide it to expand chain and it will just return it verbatim.

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:24.340
And that's all we really need to get this application spitting out our code that I can

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:31.580
then copy and paste in a fresh R session to mimic the code that the reactives are actually

00:15:31.580 --> 00:15:37.500
executing.

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:41.940
But I don't actually recommend just inlining code like this in your Shiny app.

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:45.820
We should really think about providing a better user experience.

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:49.419
There's a couple ways to do this with Shiny Meta, but I'm going to show you the more powerful

00:15:49.419 --> 00:15:54.820
approach, which is to have something like a download button and have this button call

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:59.940
this build RMD bundle from Shiny Meta, which allows you to provide a zip bundle to your

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:07.219
user with both like an RMD source file with the code that's influenced by the user input

00:16:07.219 --> 00:16:16.140
as well as the rendered output of that R markdown source.

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:23.020
So if we start with our expand chain that's generating the code to mimic the code that

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:30.460
we need for the time series visualization, we can slip that inside a download handler

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:36.780
and take the results of that expand chain call and feed it into this build RMD bundle.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:42.020
But this build RMD bundle will also need an R markdown template and here is where you

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:48.140
can specify where in your R markdown template you actually want to place the code.

00:16:48.539 --> 00:16:53.659
And this can be pretty useful when you have, say, lots of different outputs in your Shiny

00:16:53.659 --> 00:16:54.659
app.

00:16:54.659 --> 00:17:01.179
You can place them in different R markdown chunks and also like specify the output format

00:17:01.179 --> 00:17:06.619
and customize to your heart's content.

00:17:06.619 --> 00:17:14.060
So just to give you like a sense of what you can do with this sort of thing, here is basically

00:17:14.060 --> 00:17:18.900
the same data but a better interface where I can go in and select different R packages

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:21.939
and compare them in the same visualization.

00:17:21.939 --> 00:17:27.699
I can choose different transformations to the data and then finally click a download

00:17:27.699 --> 00:17:39.420
report to get that RMD source and the output or like the rendered output of that RMD source.

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:46.180
So and now that we've sort of enabled our user to interact with the Shiny app, find

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:52.420
something that they're interested in and get a permanent artifact generated by the Shiny

00:17:52.420 --> 00:18:00.660
app, in some sense what we can do is have like fully programmable dynamic reports without

00:18:00.660 --> 00:18:03.699
any programming necessary.

00:18:03.699 --> 00:18:08.219
So here what I've done, this is especially interesting if you work with dynamically updating

00:18:08.219 --> 00:18:13.900
data, I can go into my Shiny app, like find the packages that I'm interested in and then

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:18.540
I can use something like RStudio Connect to schedule this thing to run, say, every day

00:18:18.540 --> 00:18:26.020
or every month or every year and then I have like a historical permanent artifact.

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:31.219
Give you another sense of what's possible here, here is a Shiny app where I can upload

00:18:31.219 --> 00:18:35.719
some data and run an ANOVA analysis on that data.

00:18:35.719 --> 00:18:41.599
So I've uploaded a data set choosing like a response and some predictor variables, checking

00:18:41.599 --> 00:18:49.640
that the assumptions of my ANOVA analysis are okay, that I can actually run this analysis,

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:58.479
choose some different predictor variables, actually run the model, get my results of

00:18:58.479 --> 00:19:05.520
the test statistics, and then finally at the end of the day, download a report with

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:10.680
both the source and the output that I see in the application, that's all driven by the

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:15.640
data that I've uploaded and the inputs that I've chosen in the Shiny app.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:21.839
All right, so in summary, interactivity is great, but whenever we do this, we're kind

00:19:21.839 --> 00:19:30.640
of, sort of, it comes at the cost of reproducibility, but with Shiny Meta, you can, with some effort,

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:36.959
at least allow your users to get some reproducible code back out of that interactive application.

00:19:36.959 --> 00:19:41.560
And to add integration to your Shiny app, you want to identify and capture the domain

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:48.479
logic, use this dot dot operator to mark reactive reads, and then expand chain to get the code

00:19:48.479 --> 00:19:53.800
back out of the outputs that you're interested in, in the Shiny app, and then optionally,

00:19:53.800 --> 00:19:59.280
to distribute that code to users, you can provide it as a zip bundle with the RMD source

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:07.719
and results via this build RMD bundle, so thanks.

00:20:07.719 --> 00:20:15.439
We just have time for a couple quick questions.

00:20:15.439 --> 00:20:21.359
How does the use of Shiny Meta affect performance, since it seems to be doing a lot of extra

00:20:21.359 --> 00:20:22.680
evaluation?

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:31.439
So it really shouldn't affect the performance at all, really, in the sense that there's

00:20:31.439 --> 00:20:38.400
two modes of execution in Shiny Meta, so when you call expand chain, it sort of opts into

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:44.599
this meta execution mode, and that's, when that happens, it's doing some computation

00:20:44.719 --> 00:20:52.880
to generate code, but it's actually, you know, not necessarily evaluating expensive code,

00:20:52.880 --> 00:21:00.520
and that evaluation is actually totally separate from the normal execution mode that is normally,

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:06.599
the normal execution is what allows, like, the output of the time series to actually

00:21:06.599 --> 00:21:12.800
be generated in the Shiny app, that's a totally separate execution model from the generation

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:13.800
of the code.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:19.040
Okay, I think that's all we have time for questions.

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:20.040
Thanks a lot, Carson.

00:21:20.040 --> 00:21:21.040
Thank you, everybody, for coming, and have a great break.

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:21.040


